revisions.rev:
The '''men who have sex with men blood donor controversy''' is the dispute over prohibitions on donations of [[blood donation|blood]] or tissue for [[organ transplant]]s from [[men who have sex with men]] (MSM), a classification of men who engage (or have engaged in the past) in sex with other men, regardless of whether they identify themselves as [[bisexual]], [[gay]] or otherwise. Opposition to the prohibition is frequently addressed in terms of bisexual and gay men. Restrictions on donors are sometimes called "deferrals" since blood donors who are found ineligible may be found eligible at a later date. Many deferrals however are indefinite, meaning blood donors may not be accepted in the future. The restrictions vary from country to country, and in many cases men are deferred even though they have not had sex with men for many years. The restrictions affect these men and in some cases, any female sex partners. They do not otherwise affect other women, including [[women who have sex with women]]. Critics of many of the deferrals claim these policies are not supported by medical science.<ref name=Schoettes>{{cite news|last=Schoettes|first=Scott|title=Blood Donations Questions|accessdate=5 December 2012|newspaper=Adelante Magazine|date=December 2012}}</ref> <!-- dummy edit; can be deleted. -->

Many [[LGBT]] organizations view the restrictions on donation as based on [[homophobia]] and not based on valid medical concern since donations are rigorously [[HIV test|tested]] to rule out donors that are infected with known viruses such as HIV, Hepatitis B, and Hepatitis C. They state the deferrals are based on stereotypes.<ref name=Schoettes/> Proponents of the lifetime restriction defend it because of the risk of false negative test results<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeff-stier/blood-for-sale_b_52046.html |title=Blood for Sale |accessdate=2008-04-05 |last=Stier|first=Jeff |date=2007-06-13 |publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc}}</ref> and because the MSM population in developed countries tends to have a relatively high prevalence of HIV/AIDS infection.<ref name="unaids2006">UNAIDS 2006 report on the global AIDS epidemic, [http://data.unaids.org/pub/GlobalReport/2006/2006_GR_CH05_en.pdf Chapter 05], June 2006</ref> There is supporting evidence that the risk of transfusion of HIV infected blood would increase if MSM were allowed to donate blood.<ref name="telegraph1aug2013">{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8441054/Homosexual-men-allowed-to-give-blood-but-sex-banned-for-decade.html |title=Homosexual men allowed to give blood but sex banned for decade |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2013-08-01}}</ref> Opponents of prohibitions against MSM point out that screening of donors should focus on sexual behavior as well as [[safe sex]] practices since many MSM may be [[monogamy|monogamous]] or in other low risk categories.<ref name=Schoettes/><ref name="telegraph1aug2013" /> Some groups in favor of lifting the restrictions support a waiting period after the blood is donated when the donor is considered to have had behavior considered higher risk, and before it is used, to match the blood bank's window of testing methods.<ref name=Schoettes/>  Depending on the testing method used, the window to detect HIV can be as short as three weeks (NAT testing method), or as long as three months (serology testing method).<ref name=Schoettes/>

<!-- dummy edit; can be deleted. -->

==HIV/AIDS==
{{Main|Men who have sex with men#HIV/AIDS}}
In many developed countries HIV is more prevalent among [[men who have sex with men]] (MSM) than among the general population.<ref name="unaids2006"/>

In the United States in 2005, MSM, [[African Americans]], and persons engaging in high-risk heterosexual behavior accounted for respectively 49%, 49%, and 32% of new HIV diagnoses.<ref>CDC [http://www.cdc.gov/hiv/topics/surveillance/resources/reports/2005report/pdf/2005SurveillanceReport.pdf HIV/AIDS Surveillance Report: HIV Infection and AIDS in the United States and Dependent Areas, 2005.]</ref> In the United States, in 2009, African Americans accounted for 47.9% of new HIV diagnoses reported in 2009, and represented 12% of the population in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avert.org/america.htm|title=HIV and AIDS in America|publisher=avert.org}}</ref>

